#### 2000 Census

The [census](/Census) conducted in 2000 found a population of 30,271 people within the CDP. This population was distributed among 9,764 households, with 7,947 families. The population density was a substantial 7,539.9 inhabitants per square mile (2,911.2/km²). There were 9,938 housing units, resulting in an average density of 2,475.4 units per square mile (955.8/km²).

The racial makeup at the time was overwhelmingly [White](/White_(U.S._Census)), constituting 93.78% of the population. Of this, 13.7% identified as [Non-Hispanic White](/Non-Hispanic_White). [African Americans](/African_American_(U.S._Census)) represented 0.61%, [Native Americans](/Native_American_(U.S._Census)) a mere 0.04%, and [Asians](/Asian_(U.S._Census)) accounted for 0.51%. Residents identifying with [other races](/Race_(United_States_Census)) made up 2.81%, while 2.23% identified as belonging to two or more races. Critically, [Hispanic](/Hispanic_(U.S._Census)) or [Latino](/Latino_(U.S._Census)) individuals, regardless of race, comprised a significant 85.31% of the population.

In terms of household composition in 2000, 28.0% of households included children under the age of 18. Married couples living together accounted for 60.5% of households. Female householders with no husband present represented 15.7%, and 18.6% were classified as non-families. Individuals living alone constituted 14.8% of all households, with 8.6% of these individuals being 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 3.07, and the average family size was 3.33.

The age distribution in 2000 showed 18.7% of the population under 18, 7.2% between 18 and 24, 26.7% from 25 to 44, 24.4% from 45 to 64, and 23.0% aged 65 and over. The median age was 43 years. For every 100 females, there were 87.2 males, and for every 100 females aged 18 and over, there were 83.4 males.

Economically, the median income for a household in the CDP in 2000 was $40,762, with families earning a median income of $44,863. Males reported a median income of $29,629, contrasted with $24,235 for females. The [per capita income](/Per_capita_income) for the CDP was $17,264. A notable 8.5% of families and 11.8% of the population lived below the [poverty line](/Poverty_line), a statistic that held true for 13.0% of those under 18 and 13.0% of those aged 65 and over.

Linguistically, as of 2000, [Spanish](/Spanish_language) was the dominant [first language](/First_language), spoken by 88.81% of residents. [English](/English_language) served as the [mother tongue](/Mother_tongue) for 10.78% of the population.

### Government and Infrastructure

Emergency services in Westchester are provided by the [Miami-Dade Fire Rescue](/Miami-Dade_Fire_Rescue), which operates Station 3 Tropical Park within the community. For meteorological matters, the [National Weather Service](/National_Weather_Service) maintains its Miami Office on a subleased area within the [Florida International University](/Florida_International_University) campus.

### Education

Westchester is served by a robust educational infrastructure, encompassing both public and private institutions.

**Public Schools**

The [Miami-Dade County Public Schools](/Miami-Dade_County_Public_Schools) district oversees eight public schools within the community.

*   **High Schools:**
    *   [Miami Coral Park High School](/Miami_Coral_Park_High_School)
    *   [Southwest Miami Senior High School](/Southwest_Miami_Senior_High_School) (While located in [Olympia Heights](/Olympia_Heights,_Florida), it serves the southern portions of Westchester.)

*   **K-8 Schools:**
    *   Everglades K-8 Center

*   **Middle Schools:**
    *   Rockway Middle School
    *   West Miami Middle School (Though situated outside the CDP, it serves a section of Westchester.)

*   **Elementary Schools:**
    *   Banyan Elementary School
    *   Coral Park Elementary School
    *   Emerson Elementary School
    *   [Carlos Finlay](/Carlos_Finlay) Elementary School (located on the FIU campus)
    *   Rockway Elementary School
    *   Olympia Heights Elementary School (located in the former University Park CDP, it serves a southwestern section of Westchester.)

**Private Schools**

Several private educational institutions cater to the community, with many affiliated with the [Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Miami](/Roman_Catholic_Archdiocese_of_Miami).

*   [Christopher Columbus High School](/Christopher_Columbus_High_School_(Miami,_Florida)) - A Catholic private school.
*   [St. Brendan High School](/St._Brendan_High_School) - Another Catholic private school.
*   St. Agatha Catholic School - A Catholic private school located within the former University Park CDP.
*   St. Brendan Elementary School - A Catholic private school.
*   King's Christian
*   Gladeview Christian
*   [Florida Christian School](/Florida_Christian_School) - Located in [Olympia Heights](/Olympia_Heights,_Florida).

**Universities and Colleges**

*   [Florida International University](/Florida_International_University) - Formerly situated in the [University Park](/University_Park,_Florida) CDP, its main campus is a significant presence.
*   [St. John Vianney College Seminary](/Saint_John_Vianney_Seminary_(Miami)) - A Catholic private college.

**Public Libraries**

The [Miami-Dade Public Library](/Miami-Dade_Public_Library) system operates the Westchester Regional Library, providing essential community resources.

**Miscellaneous Education**

The [Miami Hoshuko](/Miami_Hoshuko), a supplementary weekend Japanese school, conducts its classes at the Iglesia Bautista de Coral Park ("Coral Park Baptist Church") in Westchester. Its administrative offices are located in [Doral, Florida](/Doral,_Florida). Established in 1984, it serves as a vital cultural and educational link for the Japanese community.

